There were many wildly different scenarios spoken of during that conversation. I think the closest thing we got to a consensus on anything was about humanity's "extinction". That being by way of virus. It only affected human-like creatures, but since the anthros were still very, very early in their uplifting, they weren't human enough to be affected by it. The uplift then stopped being artificially maintained and guided and continued on naturally, resulting in it taking either hundreds or thousands of years for them to evolve to the point of being anthros. It would leave the infrastructure of humans completely untouched except by the natural decay of not being maintained.
Spaceships really just don't make much sense except in very particular scenarios. Cryo-pods allow for much greater general opportunity in a story on an individual level than spaceships do.

Anonymous Sun 18 Apr 2021 02:43:51 No.37987580 Report
Quoted By: >>37988033 >>37989373
>>37987407
Newer unfinished ones are a lot easier to forgive than old unfinished ones. Newer unfinished ones are unfinished because they're hot off the presses and constantly getting new and interesting content. Old unfinished stories end up more like a big building project that constantly misses deadlines. It gets the big publicity, gets talked about loads, then it doesn't have the steam to keep up. Eventually people get tired of it and think they just need to wait until the next update. The problem is that when that update doesn't come for a long time, the story's relevance basically dies.
The other category is the old and truly dead stories (ala 12 O'Clock Girls and such). Those can be very nice to read sometimes as imagination fuel, or pain fuel depending on the type of person you are.
>>37987508
It's not about raw wordcount, it's about percentage of the story that's complete. I've read stories over 250k that still feel like they could do with at least another 150k.
